alyze sentimentalism not just as a literary genre but as a structure of feeling manifested in many areas: temperance testimonials, begging letters, historiography, philanthropic performance, photography, portraiture, and poetry. Essays from a variety of disciplines—American studies, literature, history, art, gender studies—deconstruct the alignment of reason, commerce, and the public sphere with men, and feelings, domesticity, and the private sphere with women.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAmerican. 4aGeneral. 4aLiterary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aBerger, Martin A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBertolini, Vincent J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurgett, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapman, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapman, Mary, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aForeman, P. Gabrielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleghorn, Cassandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGould, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendler, Glenn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendler, Glenn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPenry, Tara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaillant, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSanchez-Eppler, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSandage, Scott A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSawaya, Francesca, econtributor